    <stitle>VT-365 Diesel Engine Diagnostics (2002) - ENGINE SYMPTOMS DIAGNOSTICS - Test Procedures - Excessive Fuel
        Consumption
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="0">
        <title>Excessive Fuel Consumption</title>
        <svcprocinfo>
            <para>
                <title>Causes</title>
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Operator effects</emph>
            </para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Inaccurate record keeping or tank filling</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Winter blend or No. 1 fuel</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>High expectations</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Application effects</emph>
            </para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Heavy loading Gross Vehicle Weight (GVW)</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Low rear axle ratio</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Large frontal area</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Accessory usage (Power Takeoff, etc.)</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Additional equipment drawing fuel from vehicle fuel tanks</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Extended idle applications</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Tire size, tire condition, air pressure</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Chassis effects</emph>
            </para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Brake drag</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Cooling fan clutch locked ON</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Transmission slippage/shifting</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Fuel tank plumbing or venting</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Intake or exhaust restriction</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Engine effects</emph>
            </para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Incorrect or defective thermostat</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Defective Electronic Variable Response Turbocharger (EVRT&#8482;) operation</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Oil aeration</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Fuel system leaks</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Base engine performance loss</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Verifying Excessive Fuel Consumption Complaints</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Review operator records and fueling procedures. Measurement errors are common. Fuel
                    consumption taken only from one tank of use is susceptible to significant error because of filling
                    procedures and vehicle application differences during operation. Accurate fuel consumption must be
                    measured over time with a record of what the vehicle was doing during the measurement period.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Loss of fuel economy is normal if winter blend fuel, kerosene or No. 1 diesel fuel is
                    being used.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Review vehicle specifications to determine if fuel consumption is normal for type of
                    application and use of vehicle. (Compare consumption with similar vehicles in the same application
                    and TCAPE report).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Do all tests on Performance Diagnostic form EGED-250 or in Section 6 of this manual.
                    These tests will verify the operating condition of the following engine and chassis systems:
                </para>
                <randlist type="bullet">
                    <item>
                        <para>Intake system</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Exhaust system</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Fuel delivery and filtration</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>High pressure fuel system</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Injector operation</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>EVRT&#8482; turbocharger operation</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Oil aeration</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Base engine condition</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Electronic control system condition</para>
                    </item>
                </randlist>
                <para>If all tests are passed, the engine is operating normally.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
